16 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
17 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280 of Title 59, unless there
19 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Oklahoma
21 Community Health Workers Act".
22 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
23 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280.1 of Title 59, unless there
24 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
Req. No. 13185 Page 1

1 As used in the Oklahoma Community Health Workers Act:
2 1. "Certified community health worker" means a community health
3 worker to whom the State Department of Health has issued a
4 certificate to practice as a certified community health worker in
5 this state;
6 2. "Community health worker" means a frontline health worker
7 who has a shared understanding of and is a trusted member of the
8 community being served;
9 3. "Core competencies" are defined as the knowledge and skills
10 a certified community health worker is expected to demonstrate in
11 order to carry out the mission and goals of the profession as
12 defined by the Department through the promulgation of administrative
13 regulations in accordance with state guidelines; and
14 4. "Department" means the State Department of Health as
15 established to direct guidance, in collaboration with the State
16 Community Health Worker Association or Advisory Committee, in
17 relation to community health worker training, certification, and
18 recertification protocols.
19 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
20 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280.2 of Title 59, unless there
21 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
22 A. The State Department of Health shall establish a certificate
23 for community health workers. This certification shall be
24 voluntary.
Req. No. 13185 Page 2

1 B. A certified community health worker may:
2 1. Serve as a liaison between health and social services and
3 the community, including faith-based organizations, to facilitate
4 access to services and improve the quality and cultural competence
5 of service delivery;
6 2. Assist in identifying and communicating gaps in current
7 community and health care resources; and
8 3. Build individual and community capacity by increasing health
9 knowledge and self-sufficiency through a range of activities such as
10 outreach, community education, coaching, mentoring, social support,
11 and advocacy, including efforts within faith-based settings.
12 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
13 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1280.3 of Title 59, unless there
14 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
15 Eligibility to apply for voluntary certification in order to be
16 eligible to apply for community health worker certification, an
17 individual shall:
18 1. Be a legal United States resident;
19 2. Be a resident of Oklahoma;
20 3. Be at least eighteen (18) years of age; and
21 4. Provide evidence to the Department of his or her work
22 experience as a community health worker, demonstrating a minimum of
23 one thousand (1,000) practical hours and recommendation from a
